claude-obsidian / Claude Companion
==================================

This project builds on and is inspired by prior work. We are grateful to the
authors below.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
"The unreasonable effectiveness of HTML" — examples gallery
(vendored unmodified as a submodule, under its own Apache-2.0 license)
Author:  Thariq Shihipar
Source:  https://github.com/ThariqS/html-effectiveness
License: Apache-2.0 (at the pinned commit 0e8d447)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

How we use it
-------------
- Thariq's original HTML gallery is included **only** as a pinned git submodule
  at `upstream/html-effectiveness/`. It is never modified in place; it stays
  verbatim and remains clearly his work, attributable through its own git
  history. Clone with `--recurse-submodules` to fetch it.
- The artifact *design system* in this repo (color palette, typography, layout
  conventions, and the "single self-contained HTML document" approach) takes
  aesthetic inspiration from that gallery, but our implementation
  (`obsidian-plugin/src/artifacts/designSystem.ts` and the `claude-plugin`
  note-to-artifact skill) is an **original reformulation** — it expresses a
  similar sensibility in our own prompt and code, and is NOT a copy of the
  original HTML files.
- Project-specific variations live in
  `claude-plugin/design-system/extensions/` as additive layers, so the original
  set is never altered.

If you are Thariq and would like attribution changed or removed, please open an
issue on the repository.

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------
"Obsidian Skills" — agent skills for Obsidian's open formats
(vendored unmodified as a submodule, under its own MIT license)
Author:  Steph Ango (@kepano), CEO of Obsidian
Source:  https://github.com/kepano/obsidian-skills
License: MIT (at the pinned commit a1dc48e)
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------

How we use it
-------------
- kepano's skills are included **only** as a pinned git submodule at
  `upstream/obsidian-skills/`. They are never modified in place; they stay
  verbatim and remain clearly his work, attributable through their own git
  history. Clone with `--recurse-submodules` to fetch them.
- We treat his `obsidian-markdown`, `obsidian-bases`, and `json-canvas` skills
  as canonical *format references* for Obsidian Flavored Markdown, the Bases
  `.base` YAML format, and JSON Canvas 1.0. Our own emitters
  (`obsidian-plugin/src/bases/baseFile.ts`,
  `obsidian-plugin/src/canvas/jsonCanvas.ts`) and vault writers are original
  implementations validated against those documented formats — they are NOT
  copies of his skill files.
- His skills operate on vault *files* (and via `obsidian-cli`); our MCP bridge
  operates on the *live* vault. The two are complementary, and we recommend
  installing his skill pack alongside ours.
- The Obsidian plugin also bundles his Defuddle library
  (https://github.com/kepano/defuddle, MIT) as an ordinary npm dependency —
  it powers readable-markdown capture of web sources, the same engine behind
  the official Obsidian Web Clipper.

If you are Steph and would like attribution changed or removed, please open an
issue on the repository.

